(29, 0, 'The Art of Creative Self-Editing: From Basic to Brilliant Content', 4, 'Nithin', ' “Something more” could be the unofficial motto of everything we teach here at Copyblogger — whether it’s content marketing, copywriting, or conversion.', '1597322540_a.jpg', '<blockquote>\r\n<p>&ldquo;It&rsquo;s no secret we&rsquo;re partial to writers and other types of content creators around here. That&rsquo;s because it&rsquo;s the creators who provide the engine for traffic, funnels, and conversion in the first place.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>We&rsquo;re not talking about any ol&rsquo; content that just fills a web page. Instead, we need to create valuable messages that engage, inspire, and motivate our prospects to become who they want to be.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In other words, a healthy dose of creativity that transcends marketing and becomes&nbsp;<strong>something more.</strong>&rdquo; &ndash; Brian Clark</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\n<p>When a company fails to stand out, its marketing has a certain&nbsp;<em>something less-ness</em>&nbsp;going on. Its products or services blend in with all of the similar-looking options available.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This has nothing to do with the actual quality of a product or service. It&rsquo;s how prospects perceive the offer.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&ldquo;Something more&rdquo; could be the unofficial motto of everything we teach here at Copyblogger &mdash; whether it&rsquo;s content marketing, copywriting, or conversion.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>That&rsquo;s what Brian was getting at when&nbsp;<a href=\"https://copyblogger.com/creativity-month/\" target=\"_blank\">he wrote</a>:</p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p>&ldquo;It&rsquo;s no secret we&rsquo;re partial to writers and other types of content creators around here. That&rsquo;s because it&rsquo;s the creators who provide the engine for traffic, funnels, and conversion in the first place.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>We&rsquo;re not talking about any ol&rsquo; content that just fills a web page. Instead, we need to create valuable messages that engage, inspire, and motivate our prospects to become who they want to be.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In other words, a healthy dose of creativity that transcends marketing and becomes&nbsp;<strong>something more.</strong>&rdquo; &ndash; Brian Clark</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\n<p>When a company fails to stand out, its marketing has a certain&nbsp;<em>something less-ness</em>&nbsp;going on. Its products or services blend in with all of the similar-looking options available.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This has nothing to do with the actual quality of a product or service. It&rsquo;s how prospects perceive the offer.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2>Creative self-editing 101</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>A &ldquo;good idea&rdquo; usually isn&rsquo;t enough.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A good idea might fall flat when executed, or you could find out that the idea wasn&rsquo;t all that great to begin with.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Similarly &mdash; and this is good news for anyone who feels pressure to&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7U_e1K7RKFc\" target=\"_blank\">have brilliant ideas on command</a>&nbsp;&mdash; a mediocre idea can be developed into extraordinary marketing with the right care and attention.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You give an idea that care and attention while you edit your content.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So, I&rsquo;ve simplified the creative self-editing process into five steps. And I don&rsquo;t think I&rsquo;ve&nbsp;<em>oversimplified</em>&nbsp;how much effort these steps take, because each one has many layers.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Average content is always the result of rushing an idea to completion, which leads us to Step #1.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3><strong>Step #1: Leave enough time</strong></h3>\r\n\r\n<p>&ldquo;Something more&rdquo; could be the unofficial motto of everything we teach here at Copyblogger &mdash; whether it&rsquo;s content marketing, copywriting, or conversion.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>That&rsquo;s what Brian was getting at when&nbsp;<a href=\"https://copyblogger.com/creativity-month/\" target=\"_blank\">he wrote</a>:</p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p>&ldquo;It&rsquo;s no secret we&rsquo;re partial to writers and other types of content creators around here. That&rsquo;s because it&rsquo;s the creators who provide the engine for traffic, funnels, and conversion in the first place.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>We&rsquo;re not talking about any ol&rsquo; content that just fills a web page. Instead, we need to create valuable messages that engage, inspire, and motivate our prospects to become who they want to be.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In other words, a healthy dose of creativity that transcends marketing and becomes&nbsp;<strong>something more.</strong>&rdquo; &ndash; Brian Clark</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\n<p>When a company fails to stand out, its marketing has a certain&nbsp;<em>something less-ness</em>&nbsp;going on. Its products or services blend in with all of the similar-looking options available.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This has nothing to do with the actual quality of a product or service. It&rsquo;s how prospects perceive the offer.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2>Creative self-editing 101</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>A &ldquo;good idea&rdquo; usually isn&rsquo;t enough.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A good idea might fall flat when executed, or you could find out that the idea wasn&rsquo;t all that great to begin with.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Similarly &mdash; and this is good news for anyone who feels pressure to&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7U_e1K7RKFc\" target=\"_blank\">have brilliant ideas on command</a>&nbsp;&mdash; a mediocre idea can be developed into extraordinary marketing with the right care and attention.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You give an idea that care and attention while you edit your content.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So, I&rsquo;ve simplified the creative self-editing process into five steps. And I don&rsquo;t think I&rsquo;ve&nbsp;<em>oversimplified</em>&nbsp;how much effort these steps take, because each one has many layers.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Average content is always the result of rushing an idea to completion, which leads us to Step #1.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2>Step #1: Leave enough time</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>This is the foundation for all of the other tips in this post, as well as the other 150+ articles I&rsquo;ve written for Copyblogger.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It all comes back to leaving enough time for your ideas to mature and shine.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Creative self-editing, just like writing, needs to be done in stages. We need to&nbsp;<a href=\"https://copyblogger.com/schedule-creative-time/\" target=\"_blank\">prepare for distractions</a>, because creativity is distracting. ????</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Besides unanticipated interruptions during our work sessions, there are typical creative circumstances that we can anticipate.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I always get new ideas when I&rsquo;m in work mode. Always. And most of the time they don&rsquo;t fit into the article I&rsquo;m currently writing or editing.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Nonetheless, I need to stop what I&rsquo;m doing and explore my thoughts a bit, so I have something substantial to revisit when I&rsquo;m ready to use that topic.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3><strong>Step #2: Have fun</strong></h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Having fun is an underutilized editing tool.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>But you only have time to take breaks during your editorial review if you &hellip; leave enough time to have fun.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You&rsquo;ve probably heard of the&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wRxxF4DhJU0\" target=\"_blank\">24-hour rule for better writing</a>. Essentially, after you finish writing a draft, you wait 24 hours before you edit it. This way, you&rsquo;ll have fresh eyes and catch more mistakes.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You can use the 24-hour rule within your creative self-editing process as well &mdash; it&rsquo;s not just for catching mistakes.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Taking breaks to do something fun, unrelated to your writing and editing, gives you space to&nbsp;<a href=\"https://copyblogger.com/content-success/\" target=\"_blank\">make new connections</a>&nbsp;that add depth and nuance to rough ideas.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It may sound counterintuitive, but many important messages for your audience will emerge when you&rsquo;re not concerned about writing an important message.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '2020-08-13');
